 <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://s88610834.onlinehome.us/Orthodox/index.html" target="top"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://s88610834.onlinehome.us/skunks.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=esdras>esdras</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:maroon;><b>Administrator<br>Sir Esdras,<br>Master, Knights of the Realm,<br>Peacekeeper Extraordinaire,<br>Canadian, eh.</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 587<br> <font color=#B87333>(11/8/03 11:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=56.topic&index=19>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www3.sympatico.ca/gsmorgan/images/ADPY005.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Praying for the dead</span><hr size=1> Hey <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>WordWolf</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:<br>
<br>
I know you have kind of got this on the topic of canon, but the &quot;concept&quot; of purgatory is in the Bible - not needing to refer to deutoercanonical/apocryphal works either - even if the word is not.<br>
<br>
<br>
1Cr 15:52 In a moment, in the twinkling of an eye, at the last trump: for the trumpet shall sound, and the dead shall be raised incorruptible, and we shall be changed.<br>
<br>
There are also the verses in 1 Corinthians which deal with the judgement we receive and our deeds being rewarded or burnt away - saying the person shall be saved, but as through fire.<br>
<br>
This is the &quot;real&quot; truth about purgatory.  It is NOT a way to wash away sins per se, but a way to be transformed into the new life God has for you.  We are not the same when we enter heaven, and although Christ died for all our sins, we are still of the flesh.  The final transformation or change must take place and all our former nature of the flesh must be purged.  Purgatory is a word based on the root word of &quot;purge&quot;.  Additionally, some say that while the sin has been forgiven, it still leaves a mark on us, perhaps because we have yet to forgive ourselves.  The analogy I have heard to this is a nail (sin) in wood (our souls).  Christ's passion removed the nail, but there is still a hole.  Purgatory perfoms the final healing of that hole.<br>
<br>
Now, there is NOWHERE in Catholic doctrine that applies a temporal or spatial nature to Purgatory.  In fact, the process can be said to be instantaneous, if that actually matters for we are now in God's temporal state, which really is a-temporal (God totally unconstrained by and in control of time itself).<br>
<br>
Now, this judgement and purging of our last remains of our sinful natures likely won't be pleasant.  We will be faced with all the times we disappointed God.  So, the process might be &quot;painful&quot;.<br>
<br>
What we have is the concept of our judgement before God, something most Protestants believe.  Catholics have simply given the name &quot;Purgatory&quot; to this event - which, as I have said, has not spatial or temporal component to it.<br>
<br>
So, why pray for souls experiencing Purgatory?  Shouldn't this have already taken place by the time we pray?  Yes, in our own view of time, this is correct.  However, God is completely a-temporal.  Time does not hinder Him in any manner.  God is completely capable of hearing our prayer, hoping that a persons suffering in Purgatory is lessened.  God can then go and ensure that the persons suffering <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>will have been lessened</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Yes, that doesn't make sense to us, but for God there is not a problem to do this.<br>
<br>
Have you ever passed an accident scene and prayed something like &quot;Dear Lord, I pray that everyone involved in the accident is ok.&quot;  That's praying for something in the past - to us.  I have even heard Protestants pray for the recently deceased who they don't think had accepted God and they say &quot;Lord, I pray that Mr. X accepted Jesus before his death&quot;.  Not much different from the Pugatory thing.<br>
<br>
On a final note (sorry that this is long), Pugatory is not a halfway point between heaven and hell.  You are saved or not.  Period.  Those going to hell are going to hell, and those going to heaven are going to heaven - once we have faced God and have been changed/purged/whatever word. <p>Christians know that it is not possible to reject or ignore God without demeaning man.<br>
- John Paul II at WYD 2002<br>
