<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Well here's one protestant who doesn't pray for things in the past because I know what's past is past.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes, for us the past is the past, but not for God.<br>
<br>
God <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>created</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> time.  He is not bound by time.  Although it is hard to say whether God controls time, exists outside of time or is simply not bound by time is hard to say.  It may even be a combination of all three, but the point is that we all acknowledge God as the creator of the universe.  Time is a component of the universe (some call it the fourth dimension) and we experience time in a linear fashion.  God, being the creator of that dimension should &quot;logically&quot; exert some control over it as He has control over the rest of His creation.<br>
<br>
To say that God is bound by time would be to limit His power. <br>
<br>
Therefore, to many it is acceptable to pray for something that has already happened where we do not really know what the outcome is.  We cannot pray for someone we know has broken a leg (for example) not to have broken a leg.  It is something that is already a part of our consciousness and will not be changed.  However, when it is something where we don't have a knowledge of the outcome, it is permissable for us to pray as God still has command over what has transpired.  That is why you will hear many pray for someone who died that they accpeted Christ at a point before their death.<br>
<br>
Anyway, this isn't the easiest topic to discuss, as it kind of goes beyond our concept of linear time.  <br>
<br>
There isn't anything is scripture that specifically prohibits praying for something in the past either.  So I see it as one of those gray areas where it doesn't make a huge difference in the grand scheme of things. <p>Christians know that it is not possible to reject or ignore God without demeaning man.<br>
- John Paul II at WYD 2002<br>
